          "Meets Expectations": "Writes clean, maintainable, and well-tested code. Follows established architectural patterns and team best practices. Adept at debugging.",
          "Exceeds Expectations": "Anticipates edge cases and designs for scalability. Leaves code better than they found it. Deeply understands system architecture.",
          "Outstanding": "Architects complex, highly scalable solutions. Sets technical standards for the team. Introduces new technologies that significantly improve performance or capability."
        }
      },
      {
        "category_name": "Execution & Delivery",
        "weight_percentage": 30,
        "criteria": {
          "Needs Improvement": "Frequently misses deadlines or delivers incomplete features. Poor at breaking down tasks. Fails to communicate blockers promptly.",
          "Meets Expectations": "Delivers assigned tasks on time and to specification. Provides accurate estimations. Communicates progress and blockers clearly.",
          "Exceeds Expectations": "Consistently delivers ahead of schedule or takes on additional scope. Identifies and clears blockers proactively. Streamlines development workflows.",
          "Outstanding": "Drives the delivery of major, high-stakes projects. Optimizes team-wide execution processes (e.g., CI/CD pipelines, agile rituals) reducing overall time-to-market."
        }
      },
      {
        "category_name": "Teamwork, Communication & Code Review",
        "weight_percentage": 20,
        "criteria": {
          "Needs Improvement": "Communication is unclear or abrasive. Rarely reviews others' code or leaves unhelpful feedback. Siloes information.",
          "Meets Expectations": "Communicates effectively with peers and stakeholders. Participates actively in code reviews with constructive feedback. Good team player.",
          "Exceeds Expectations": "Proactively shares knowledge (e.g., tech talks, documentation). Mentors junior engineers. Code reviews are thorough and educational.",
          "Outstanding": "Acts as a cultural multiplier. Seamlessly collaborates across different departments (Product, Design, QA). Resolves complex technical disagreements amicably."
        }
      },
      {
        "category_name": "Initiative & Problem Ownership",
        "weight_percentage": 20,
        "criteria": {
          "Needs Improvement": "Waits to be assigned tasks. Ignores systemic issues (e.g., technical debt, flaky tests). Deflects blame when things go wrong.",
          "Meets Expectations": "Takes full ownership of assigned tasks from conception to deployment. Learns from mistakes and applies fixes to prevent recurrence.",
          "Exceeds Expectations": "Identifies areas for improvement (technical or process-oriented) and volunteers to fix them. Takes responsibility for broader system reliability.",
          "Outstanding": "Champions major technical or process innovations. Identifies core business problems and proactively designs engineering solutions to address them."
        }
      }
    ],
    "review_process_guidelines": {
      "self_evaluation": "The engineer should rate themselves against these criteria and provide specific, linked examples (PRs, design docs, project epics) to justify their ratings.",
      "manager_evaluation": "The manager will synthesize peer feedback, code metrics, and project outcomes against this rubric to provide a finalized rating.",
      "goal_setting": "Areas marked as 'Needs Improvement' or 'Meets Expectations' should form the basis of the individual's growth plan for the next review cycle."
    }
  }
}
```

